al;background:none;opacity:1;border:0;margin:0;padding:0;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0"><img alt="In 2021, The Verge took an interactive county-by-county look at the broadband gap." src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" decoding="async" data-nimg="fill" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%;object-fit:cover"/><noscript><img alt="In 2021, The Verge took an interactive county-by-county look at the broadband gap." loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-nimg="fill" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%;object-fit:cover" sizes="(max-width: 1023px) 100vw, 744px" srcSet="https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/376x220/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 376w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/384x225/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 384w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/415x243/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 415w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/480x281/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 480w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/540x316/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 540w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/640x375/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 640w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/750x440/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 750w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/828x485/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 828w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/1080x633/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 1080w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/1200x703/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 1200w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/1440x844/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 1440w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/1920x1125/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 1920w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/2048x1200/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 2048w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/2400x1407/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg 2400w" src="https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:1551x909/2400x1407/filters:focal(776x455:777x456):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733499/chrome_li7s2BTUkF.jpg"/></noscript></span></div></div></figure></div></div><div class="duet--media--caption pt-6 font-polysans-mono text-12 font-light leading-130 tracking-1"><figcaption class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup inline text-gray-13 dark:text-gray-e9 [&amp;&gt;a:hover]:text-black [&amp;&gt;a:hover]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;&gt;a:hover]:text-gray-e9 dark:[&amp;&gt;a:hover]:shadow-underline-gray-63 [&amp;&gt;a]:shadow-underline-gray-13 dark:[&amp;&gt;a]:shadow-underline-gray-63">In 2021, <em>The Verge</em> took an <a href="/22418074/broadband-gap-america-map-county-microsoft-data">interactive county-by-county look at the broadband gap</a>.</figcaption> <cite class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup inline not-italic text-gray-63 dark:text-gray-bd [&amp;&gt;a:hover]:text-gray-63 [&amp;&gt;a:hover]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;&gt;a:hover]:text-gray-bd dark:[&amp;&gt;a:hover]:shadow-underline-gray [&amp;&gt;a]:shadow-underline-gray-63 dark:[&amp;&gt;a]:text-gray-bd dark:[&amp;&gt;a]:shadow-underline-gray">Image: The Verge</cite></div></div></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white min-h-[80px] first-letter:float-left first-letter:mr-18 first-letter:font-polysans-mono first-letter:text-100 first-letter:font-medium first-letter:leading-[.72]  first-letter:selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:first-letter:text-franklin">But will BEAD funds be pouring into an illegally rigged playing field? That’s the question that’s been bugging me for weeks. </p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">Because no matter how much Biden’s infrastructure bill was weakened, the final federal law still says states “may not exclude” public entities from a chance at the grant money. And yet, the federal agency responsible for BEAD broadband dollars apparently doesn’t agree. </p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">Remember the 2 percent deduction from the infrastructure act? That $849 million helps fund the National Telecommunications and Information Administration (<a href="https://ntia.gov/">NTIA</a>), which lays out all the requirements for states and their subcontractors to get BEAD funding <a href="https://broadbandusa.ntia.doc.gov/sites/default/files/2022-05/BEAD%20NOFO.pdf">in this 98-page document</a> (pdf). But the NTIA has seemingly decided not to challenge the states. Even as the agency “strongly encourages” waiving pre-existing laws, it’s simultaneously assuring states it won’t act if they ignore that request. </p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component clear-both block"><div class="my-9"><div class="transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out"><div class="fixed inset-0 h-[110vh] w-full bg-white transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out z-[-1] cursor-default opacity-0" role="button" aria-label="Close" tabindex="0"></div><div role="button" aria-label="Zoom" tabindex="0" class="visible z-30 w-full origin-center transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out cursor-zoom-in"><figure class="transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out lg:mx-0"><div><div class="duet--media--content-warning relative" style="padding-top:36.08247422680412%"><span style="box-sizing:border-box;display:block;overflow:hidden;width:initial;height:initial;background:none;opacity:1;border:0;margin:0;padding:0;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0"><img alt="The law says “may not exclude.” But the NTIA says preexisting state exclusions don’t count." src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" decoding="async" data-nimg="fill" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%;object-fit:cover"/><noscript><img alt="The law says “may not exclude.” But the NTIA says preexisting state exclusions don’t count." loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-nimg="fill" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%;object-fit:cover" sizes="(max-width: 1023px) 100vw, 744px" srcSet="https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/376x136/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 376w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/384x139/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 384w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/415x150/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 415w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/480x173/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 480w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/540x195/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 540w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/640x231/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 640w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/750x271/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 750w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/828x299/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 828w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/1080x390/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 1080w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/1200x433/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 1200w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/1440x520/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 1440w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/1920x693/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 1920w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/2048x739/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 2048w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/2400x866/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 2400w" src="https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/2400x866/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg"/></noscript></span></div></div></figure></div><div class="z-1 w-full hidden"><figure class="transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out lg:mx-0"><div><div class="duet--media--content-warning relative" style="padding-top:36.08247422680412%"><span style="box-sizing:border-box;display:block;overflow:hidden;width:initial;height:initial;background:none;opacity:1;border:0;margin:0;padding:0;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0"><img alt="The law says “may not exclude.” But the NTIA says preexisting state exclusions don’t count." src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" decoding="async" data-nimg="fill" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%;object-fit:cover"/><noscript><img alt="The law says “may not exclude.” But the NTIA says preexisting state exclusions don’t count." loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-nimg="fill" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%;object-fit:cover" sizes="(max-width: 1023px) 100vw, 744px" srcSet="https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/376x136/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 376w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/384x139/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 384w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/415x150/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 415w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/480x173/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 480w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/540x195/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 540w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/640x231/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 640w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/750x271/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 750w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/828x299/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 828w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/1080x390/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 1080w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/1200x433/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 1200w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/1440x520/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 1440w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/1920x693/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 1920w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/2048x739/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 2048w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/2400x866/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg 2400w" src="https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:582x210/2400x866/filters:focal(291x105:292x106):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24733463/may_not_exclude.jpg"/></noscript></span></div></div></figure></div></div><div class="duet--media--caption pt-6 font-polysans-mono text-12 font-light leading-130 tracking-1"><figcaption class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup inline text-gray-13 dark:text-gray-e9 [&amp;&gt;a:hover]:text-black [&amp;&gt;a:hover]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;&gt;a:hover]:text-gray-e9 dark:[&amp;&gt;a:hover]:shadow-underline-gray-63 [&amp;&gt;a]:shadow-underline-gray-13 dark:[&amp;&gt;a]:shadow-underline-gray-63"><em>The law says “may not exclude.” But the NTIA says preexisting state exclusions don’t count.</em></figcaption> <cite class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup inline not-italic text-gray-63 dark:text-gray-bd [&amp;&gt;a:hover]:text-gray-63 [&amp;&gt;a:hover]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;&gt;a:hover]:text-gray-bd dark:[&amp;&gt;a:hover]:shadow-underline-gray [&amp;&gt;a]:shadow-underline-gray-63 dark:[&amp;&gt;a]:text-gray-bd dark:[&amp;&gt;a]:shadow-underline-gray">Screenshot by Sean Hollister / The Verge</cite></div></div></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">While the NTIA does interpret the law as banning new restrictions, the only thing states <em>have</em> to do about pre-existing restrictions is to “disclose each unsuccessful application affected by such laws and describe how those laws impacted the decision to deny the application.” It’s effectively a grandfather clause, where the only penalty is paperwork.</p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">And while the NTIA does reserve the right to “determine whether the use of funds” complies with both the letter and spirit of the law, an NTIA representative <a href="https://www.fiercetelecom.com/telecom/municipal-broadband-laws-probably-wont-delay-bead-funding">has already been telling states (and told <em>FierceTelecom</em></a>)<em> </em>that BEAD funding won’t be delayed to states with pre-existing laws that restrict municipal broadband. Even in places like Nebraska, where most forms of municipal broadband are straight-up banned, the state’s broadband director said he expects no delay or reduction in federal dollars. </p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">NTIA spokesperson Virginia Bring repeatedly deflected our questions about the legal discrepancy between the federal and state laws. None of the agency’s answers to <em>The Verge</em> addressed it at all. Two telecommunication lawyers confirmed to me that the legal discrepancy is real — but suggested the NTIA could get tangled up in a lawsuit if it tried to use the federal law to preempt state ones. </p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">When I ask veteran tell-it-like-it-is telecom reporter <a href="https://www.techdirt.com/user/kbode/">Karl Bode</a> about the whole BEAD situation, he tells me: “This is a historic infusion of broadband subsidies that will absolutely result in a lot of amazing progress. At the same time there’s just endless potential for fraud and misuse of funding, given monopoly telecom’s influence on the legislative process.”</p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">But, he points out, some states may at least try to level the playing field before it’s too late. </p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">Colorado used to be the <em>17th</em> state with laws keeping local entities from easily erecting their own networks. But on May 1st, <a href="https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb23-183">the state repealed every one of them</a>. Colorado no longer prioritizes private telecom bids, no longer requires a referendum to build a municipal network, and no longer keeps local governments from creating their own middle-mile infrastructure.</p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">In Washington, there’s even a bill in committee that would <a href="https://www.telecompetitor.com/washington-bill-tests-limits-of-state-bead-authority/"><em>require</em> BEAD funding to be spent only on open-access networks</a>, making it less desirable for big business to invest. </p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component clear-both block md:float-left md:mr-30 md:w-[320px] lg:-ml-100"><div class="duet--recirculation--related-list mb-40"><h3 class="mb-16 font-polysans-mono text-14 font-medium leading-120 -tracking-1 text-blurple after:pl-8 after:content-[&#x27;/&#x27;]">Related</h3><ul class="list-disc pl-18 font-polysans text-16 font-medium leading-110 marker:text-franklin"><li class="mb-16 pl-12"><a class="hover:shadow-underline-black" href="/22418074/broadband-gap-america-map-county-microsoft-data">This is a map of America’s broadband problem</a></li><li class="mb-16 pl-12"><a class="hover:shadow-underline-black" href="/2022/11/18/23466705/fcc-new-broadband-maps-internet-united-states">The long-awaited US broadband internet maps are here — for you to challenge</a></li></ul></div></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">Some states are challenging <a href="/2022/11/18/23466705/fcc-new-broadband-maps-internet-united-states">the FCC’s broadband maps, too</a>. That’s important because the law requires that states prioritize unserved and underserved regions to help close the digital divide, but that requires <em>knowing where they are</em>. Historically, the FCC has let the wolves guard the henhouse by relying on ISPs to truthfully say which houses they cover — data that the FCC didn’t even audit. </p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">Lastly, while the NTIA may be grandfathering in <em>old</em> laws restricting municipal broadband, the agency does hint it could step in if states make things even harder than before. Before it approves a state’s “final proposal,” the NTIA says it will “consider” whether any “new laws, regulations, policies, procedures, or any other form of rule or restriction” winds up excluding “any potential providers from eligibility.”  </p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component"><p class="duet--article--dangerously-set-cms-markup duet--article--standard-paragraph mb-20 font-fkroman text-18 leading-160 -tracking-1 selection:bg-franklin-20 dark:text-white dark:selection:bg-blurple [&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-franklin dark:[&amp;_a:hover]:shadow-highlight-blurple [&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-black dark:[&amp;_a]:shadow-underline-white">Again, the NTIA will only “consider” those things before granting its approval, but at least that’s a veiled threat instead of nothing at all.</p></div><div class="duet--article--article-body-component clear-both block w-full md:ml-[-100px] md:w-outdent"><div class="my-9"><div class="transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out"><div class="fixed inset-0 h-[110vh] w-full bg-white transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out z-[-1] cursor-default opacity-0" role="button" aria-label="Close" tabindex="0"></div><div role="button" aria-label="Zoom" tabindex="0" class="visible z-30 w-full origin-center transition-all duration-300 ease-in-out cursor-zoom-in"><figure class="transition-all durat