\u003ethe Bipartisan Infrastructure Deal\u003c/a\u003e, which was finally signed as the Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act. The $100 billion shrunk to $65 billion, then to $42.45 billion for last-mile connections to people’s homes — technically $41.6 billion, after a 2 percent cut for feds to administer the program. And surprise, surprise: \u003ca href=\"https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/PLAW-117publ58/pdf/PLAW-117publ58.pdf\"\u003ethe final law\u003c/a\u003e (pdf) didn’t prioritize local networks \u003cem\u003eat all\u003c/em\u003e."},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyPullquote","placement":{"id":"x38kLh","alignment":"HANG_LEFT"},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyPullquote","quote":{"html":"Biden’s proposal could have launched a thousand new Ammons"}},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"72Kgtq","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"States can’t outright exclude local networks from grant eligibility under Biden’s infrastructure deal. (It says “may not exclude” right in the law.) But they’re only required to submit a “description” of how they intend to coordinate with local governments and “ascertain…whether” it makes sense to establish co-ops or public-private partnerships… or not. After that, they can hand the grants straight to big corporations. And in nearly one-third of the US, that decision may have already been made. "},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"2t00xa","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"As of this article’s publication, \u003ca href=\"https://broadbandnow.com/report/municipal-broadband-roadblocks\"\u003e16 states have laws\u003c/a\u003e aimed blatantly at protecting telecom incumbents from pesky public competition. Did you know the state of Michigan only lets you build a network \u003cem\u003eif\u003c/em\u003e enough private companies don’t bid? Florida requires local officials to explain how their network will be \u003cem\u003eprofitable\u003c/em\u003e within four years, as if profits were the point of fixing the digital divide. Nevada will only let towns and counties with tiny populations erect their own networks. Virginia local networks \u003ca href=\"https://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/title56/chapter15/section56-484.7:1/#:~:text=The%20prices%20charged,such%20governmental%20entity\"\u003earen’t allowed to charge less than the incumbents\u003c/a\u003e — it’s illegal to make the internet more affordable! "},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"qCG6ut","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"These laws weren’t just \u003cem\u003esupported\u003c/em\u003e by Big Telecom, by the way — some were effectively written by telecom lobbyists. \u003ca href=\"https://publicintegrity.org/inequality-poverty-opportunity/alec-based-restrictions-on-city-run-internet-at-risk-after-fcc-ruling/\"\u003eThey can reportedly be traced back\u003c/a\u003e to a model law written in 2002 by ALEC, \u003ca href=\"https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2012/05/31/154077536/wal-mart-pulls-out-of-group-that-advocates-stand-your-ground-laws\"\u003ea right-wing legislative group\u003c/a\u003e whose donors \u003ca href=\"https://www.prwatch.org/news/2019/05/13474/comcast-latest-telecommunications-company-drop-alec\"\u003epreviously included\u003c/a\u003e AT\u0026amp;T, Comcast, Cox, Lumen, and Verizon, and which would \u003ca href=\"https://www.inquirer.com/business/comcast/comcast-alec-lobbying-conservative-david-horowitz-verizon-20190610.html\"\u003eallegedly invite state legislators to meet telecom companies\u003c/a\u003e at fancy hotels. "},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyImage","placement":{"id":"UwaXM0","alignment":"WIDE_BLOCK"},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyImage","contentW